First, you'll need to have a Discord account and a Discord server where you can run the bot. You can create a new server or use an existing one. Once you have a server, you can create a channel where you want to run the bot.

1. Install the Discord.js library:
   ```bash
   npm install discord.js
   ```

2. Create a new JavaScript file (e.g., `bot.js`) and include the Discord.js library:
   ```javascript
   const { Client, WebSockets } = require('discord.js');
   ```

3. Create a new bot instance:
   ```javascript
   const { Bot, Member, Message } = require('discord.js');

   const bot = new Bot();
   bot.channel = 'your-channel-name'; // Replace with the name of your channel
   bot.eventSource = new WebSocketsSource(bot, 'ws://your-channel-name');
   bot.eventSource.onmessage = handleEvent;
   bot.run();
   ```

4. Set up the `handleEvent` function to handle the `/ban` command. This function will be called whenever a member sends a message to the channel:
   ```javascript
   function handleEvent(message) {
       const member = message.from;
       const message = message.content;

       // Check if the message is a slash command
       if (member && member.content.startsWith("/ban")) {
           const messageId = message.channel.id;
           const banReason = message.content.match(/ban(.*?)\n.*?/)[1];
           const banTarget = message.from;
           bot.ban(banReason, banTarget, messageId, message, member);

           console.log('Banned member:', banTarget);
       }
   }

   // Register the `handleEvent` function with the bot
   bot.eventSource.on('message', handleEvent);
   ```

5. Run the bot:
   ```bash
   node bot.js
   ```

Now, when you join the channel and send the `/ban` command, it will ban the specified member. The member will receive a message indicating that they have been banned.

This is a simple example of how to use Discord.js to create a bot with a single command. You can expand upon this by adding more features, such as sending messages to the banned member, or implementing additional commands. Just remember to use the slash command syntax and handle the `/ban` command appropriately. Good luck!

To convert markdown to HTML in C++, you can use the `html` library, which is part of the C++ Standard Library (C++ STL). The `html` library provides functions to escape and remove characters that are not part of HTML, which is necessary for converting markdown to HTML.

Here is a simple function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <string/char.h>

using HTML::Entities = std::string::std::char_type;

void convertMarkdownToHTML(std::string& inputText) {
    std::vector<HTML::Entities> entities;
    for (char c : inputText) {
        if (c == '\n' || c == '\r') {
            entities.push_back(HTML::Entities::space);
        } else if (c == '\t') {
            entities.push_back(HTML::Entities::tab);
        } else if (c == '\f') {
            entities.push_back(HTML::Entities::formfeed);
        } else {
            entities.push_back(HTML::Entities::char);
        }
    }
    std::string html = std::make_unique(HTML::Entities("".join(entities)))
    inputText = html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "Here is some <code>code</code> with <em>emphasized text</em> and <strong>strong text</strong>.";
    convertMarkdownToHTML(markdown);
    std::cout << markdown << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

